Services running at /etc/systemd/system/<alert-type>-alerts.service

1️⃣ Create ONE template service
📄 /etc/systemd/system/system-health-alerts@.service
[Unit]
Description=System Health Alert (%i)
After=network-online.target
Wants=network-online.target

[Service]
Type=simple
User=root

# Explicit environment (robust under systemd)
Environment=HOME=/home/hpserver
Environment=PATH=/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin

# %i expands to instance name
ExecStart=/home/hpserver/System_Scripts/System_Health_Monitor/monitors/telegram/%i.sh

Restart=always
RestartSec=10

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

2️⃣ Enable all monitors using the template
Enable + start ALL at once
sudo systemctl daemon-reload

sudo systemctl enable --now \
  system-health-alerts@cpu_load.service \
  system-health-alerts@cpu_temp.service \
  system-health-alerts@gpu_temp.service \
  system-health-alerts@dust_cooling.service

3️⃣ Verify (clean & beautiful)
systemctl status system-health-alerts@*


Example output:

● system-health-alerts@cpu_temp.service    active (running)
● system-health-alerts@battery_monitor.service  active (running)
● system-health-alerts@dust_cooling.service     active (running)


Logs per instance:

journalctl -u system-health-alerts@cpu_temp.service